a 16G dump file doesn't contain 16G of data why would you think it did? DDL and DML consume CPU and an import can be CPU-intensive so, what exactly is the problem you're trying to 'solve'? hmmm, okay, so I guess that response was wasted on you why SHOULD it??? are your tablespaces auto-extend??? are they filled to capacity and expanding? on the file system they do in Oracle they probably are pretty empty and how large are your tablespaces now? how large did you create them?? unless they are autoextend you will NOT see disk usage increase not until YOU expand a tablespace by adding a datafile this 'few k per second' you see is proably a log file from the imp session are they FILLED to capacity? probably not until they need to extend they won't and your disk usage won't increase look, when you create a tablespace Oracle creates a datafile that consumes filesystem space but is essentially empty with respect to Oracle when Oracle says it's full then it will extend of course you set LIMITS on how much these files can extend ... because unlimited growth is, well, foolish this would be a really good time to visit http://tahiti.oracle.com and read the Concepts guide ooooooooookay should they? have you checked lately? so??? I'd be querying dba_data_files and dba_free_space to find out how full these tablespaces are I'd be LOOKING at the desc for each of those tables and figuring it out you'll need an outer join to get usable results if a tablespace is full SELECT SUBSTR(tablespace_name, 1, 20) "TABLESPACE_NAME", COUNT(*) "FRAGMENTS", TRUNC(SUM(BYTES)/COUNT(*))/1024 "AVG_FREE", MIN(BYTES)/1024 "MIN_FREE", MAX(BYTES)/1024 "MAX_FREE", SUM(BYTES)/1024 "SUM_FREE" FROM dba_free_space GROUP BY tablespace_name; that will show you free space in a tablespac remember if there is NO free space you won't get the tablespace name and you won't have a row for that tablespace this is why you need an outer join between dba_free_Space and dba_data_files SUM(a.bytes) / b.bytes * 100) "% FREE" FROM dba_free_space a, dba_data_files b WHERE a.file_id (+) = b.file_id GROUP BY a.tablespace_name, a.file_id, b.bytes ORDER BY a.file_id; let me try that again check your pm the formatting may be a bit off

034deaa60f879dab1136169e1c0bbcb4: so you're using an application cache? 034deaa60f879dab1136169e1c0bbcb4: you may need to do some reading up on the app cache :)  In a nutshell, if one is available, it's checked on visit; if it's had any changes to the text (even as comments), it's treated as a change, and all the resources are downloaded again.  You'll then need to reload the page to see the changes. Personally, I generate it with a script, which includes a comment based on the last modified date within certain directories other people use a timestamp or something similar - just be careful it's the same at start and end of the load

Amazon's new HTML5 kindle implementation is interesting - wonder how they're doing the page calculations so fast? They're also not doing anything special with the manifest, which is interesting considering some of the in-the-wild iOS issues we're running into would love to know who did that https://read.amazon.com/ :) yup - cloud synching, offline reading, etc, all in HTML5 decent compatibility, too yeah :)  When I tried it on the iPad I assumed it must be pre-generated (one font, five sizes) but‚Ä¶ you can also try it on the desktop, with different window sizes.  It's not snapping to paragraphs; it loads chunks into the page, but they're not fixed chapter breaks or anything I haven't had time to delve into it properly but it's pretty damn fast and doesn't appear to be using precalculations E Each word is in a span, and some have ids, so they might be doing an optimised walk to find page boundaries within the current "blob" of loaded text but that still doesn't explain being able to jump to another blob WebKit-only‚Ä¶ not too surprising I suppose, if they're targeting mobile devices Interestingly, when I set Safari to use the iPad user agent, it still showed a desktop screenshot (differently to an actual iPad), so it's not using [just] UAs

paul actually operates the internet switchboard. irc. so asynchronous, it makes you question your very packets. make it look sleek and get twitter to do the rest =) the only way an aggregator can succeed is to make people feel their contributions aren't contributions. make it sleek, make adding apps you heard of a one click process, reviews without login (but added weight to reviews by proper users), and you can get some good momentum going. and make sure the name isn't a common word that gets lost in the search engines or your runup to fame will be cut short by people not being able to google for it because if I have to take the effort to help you out, I have better things to do with my time. unless you have something really cool to offer, there's no reward for me as a user to go through the effort of trying to get in and having a more convenient place to find html5 apps, when it's just starting up, is not rewarding. it's only the promise of a reward later on, when enough people have helped you build it up. so invite only is great if you already have a considerable product sitting behind the login portal. but for a crowd sourced site... probably not the right model. #iphonedev (/list keyword is your friend =D) (although /list is your worst enemy) or, given how people make mobile sites, "sparse" vs. "full" I've seen the opposite too, where mobile means "useless" and real means "Actually showing images" if you're in a modern western country, say, and you're on an unlimited or too-much-to-user-per-month data plan, you don't care about saving b/w. You want a good looking webapp or site. with 1ghz+ procs, time is fast becoming irrelevant too navigation vs use time, though, yes. you want to drive down the first while keeping the second high but that's the first principle of user interface design, really. I'm not touching third world. The way the web and mobiles are user there is so radically different that I simply don't understand their use model. *are used true, but you shouldn't sacrifice content over it too readily it's particularly interesting when tablets are involved. 10af6afd5b4cecd7f17a94fba46fc2ee - what is and isn't an "html5 mobile app"? actually I'm asking about all 3 terms what makes a site "html5" in your opinion vs not? is just using the HTML5 doctype enough? so what makes the difference then as far as inclusion in such a "directory"? and what makes a site "mobile"? you may want to take a look at Jeremy Keith's recent presentation "There Is No Mobile Web" and related blog posts: http://adactio.com/journal/4860/ and http://adactio.com/journal/4862/ he also touches in that first blog post about the problem with labeling something a "web app" why not characterize it as "flexible" environment rather than "mobile"? where sparse usually means good content/copy design, and full means noisy and full of crap that wastes bandwidth and no one looks at? I say flexible rather than mobile because the #/range/uses of mobile devices has exploded 0de37da1d654c10aed33d7b7347b8e3b - I've seen dumbed down "mobile" sites too and they're quite annoying. You can't assume mobile means fast - even in western countries. The networks fail and lag all the time. e.g. slow connections: conferences, dialup, third world, rural cell coverage, urban subways/BART, protests, disasters. 10af6afd5b4cecd7f17a94fba46fc2ee - yes - was responding to 0de37da1d654c10aed33d7b7347b8e3b's idealistic assessment of a "a modern western country" you have to care about bandwidth even in "a modern western country" otherwise your app/site/page sucks for the same reason, you can't depend on Javascript either (assuming you're designing for "flexible/mobile" rather than desktop/hardline environments) e.g. what happens on a slow network when users click an AJAX #!-link before the JS loads? nothing. slow net is like JS-off. 0de37da1d654c10aed33d7b7347b8e3b - hence why "mobile version" is bad design clean and flexible design works everywhere, mobile, desktop, tablet etc. The new Boston Globe design is a good example Jeremy's blog post discusses it: http://adactio.com/journal/4862/ and the clincher at the bottom of the post - the new Boston Globe even works reasonably on the old Apple Newton

tantek: I'm kind of attached to hMachine, but if lightening strikes I think i can make necessary adjustments... maybe uMachine, although i want to emphasize that the tool can be used for more than just Microformats. It's for POSH in general hyperMachine seems verbose Well, first of all, it's a Ruby library and DSL for creating html parsers. So you can easily define a posh format and extract data from it using the simple microformat patterns (datetime, valueclass, abbrtitle). It has classes for parsing a handful of microformats right now, more on the way. Along with being a library, it's also a CLI so you can do something like this, in UNIX: curl http://markwunsch.com | hmachine --hcard > 4fa565c0c276375bdcf51e81db1beccb.vcf Will produce a vcard. And it also provides simple extensions for Ruby's standard objects. Array.to_ordered_list Hash.to_definition_list

 basically, websockets looks like HTTP, but at what point does accepting HTTP input that's more lax than the websocket client input constitute a violation of the protocol... ...requirements? s/enforced/required/, then the client is required to follow the exact steps given in the draft the server, it seems, has latitude to accept more than that is the server required to accept input from a client that doesn't actually follow the strictures of the client-processing section? for regression testing, it doesn't matter what the server does, it just has to check that the client sends exactly the right bytes a regression test suite server and a production server are completely different you can't, e.g., use apache to do serious regression testing of client-side http behaviour i don't really see how a regression-testing server framework can be unsafe -- it has to accept any input whatsoever 8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: an "in production" server is one serving end-user traffic 8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: a regression testing server is one used to test another tool's implementation so an in-production server can do things like disconnect if the input is bogus but a regression testing server needs to report pass/fail for all inputs eca88ce0deea1275223afe139b2595e2: here um nothing beyond what the spec says as far as i can tell how do you mean? just call them character references the problem is calling &#nnnn; and &#xnnnn; entities is wrong. In SGML and XML, &foo; is an general entity ref. &amp;, for example, is commonly called a character entity ref because it only contains 1 char but officially, there is no such thing as a character entity ref in SGML or XML ok yeah I recommend only using entity when you need to distinguish between &#...; and &foo;
